  "prompt": "What's the origin of the expression \"Yippee Ki-Yay\"?",
  "response": "The expression \"Yippee Ki-Yay\" is often associated with the character John McClane, played by Bruce Willis, in the \"Die Hard\" film series. It is a catchphrase that McClane uses, particularly in the first film released in 1988, and has since become iconic in popular culture.\n\nThe phrase itself can be traced back to cowboy and Western films, where similar expressions were used to convey excitement or enthusiasm. It evokes the spirit of the American West and the adventurous, carefree attitude often associated with cowboys. However, the specific phrasing \"Yippee Ki-Yay\" gained prominence and widespread recognition primarily through its use in \"Die Hard.\"\n\nThe catchphrase has since been adopted in various contexts and continues to be referenced in movies, TV shows, and other media.",
